1) Circuit Symbols & Components

  • Learn to recognise standard circuit symbols for cell, battery, power supply (d.c. and a.c.), switch, lamp, resistor (fixed/variable), thermistor, LDR, heater, potential divider, transformer, motor, generator, ammeter, voltmeter, diode/LED, fuse, relay coil, and electric bell.
  • Remember: ammeter is connected in series to measure current I in A; voltmeter is connected in parallel to measure p.d. V.
  • Polarities matter: the long line is positive for a cell; for diodes the triangle/arrow shows allowed direction of conventional current.
Teaching tips & guidance
  • Starter: give students a mixed sheet of symbols — 30‑second ‘snap’ to name as many as possible.
  • Misconception: students often wire voltmeters in series. Show a quick demo to emphasise parallel connection.
  • Link to safety: point out the fuse symbol and ask where it belongs in a plug (live wire).

2) Thermistor (Temperature-Dependent Resistor)

  • A thermistor has resistance R that varies with temperature.
  • NTC thermistor (common in GCSE): higher temperature → lower resistance; lower temperature → higher resistance.
  • Use in temperature sensors (thermostats, fire alarms). Equation V = I R links V, I, and R.
Teaching tips & guidance
  • Demo: warm the thermistor gently with your hand or hairdryer and watch current/voltage change.
  • Link graphs: discuss why resistance falls (more charge carriers available).

Answer: resistor

Answer: Negative Temperature Coefficient

Answer: sensors

3) LDR (Light-Dependent Resistor)

  • An LDR has resistance R that varies with light intensity.
  • More light → lower resistance; less light → higher resistance.
  • Used in automatic lights and camera exposure. At constant V, as R falls, I increases.
Teaching tips & guidance
  • Room activity: shine a phone torch vs cover with a book — predict and observe the voltage change in a divider.
  • Common slip: confusing current and light direction arrows on the diagram — clarify icons.

Answer: V = I R

Answer: higher

Answer: variable resistor

Answer: bright light
Units of current are…
Answer: A
Units of resistance are…
Answer: Ω
Units of potential difference are…
Answer: V

4) Diodes

  • A diode allows current in one direction only (forward direction).
  • In reverse bias, the diode blocks current.
  • Used for rectification (turning a.c. into d.c.) and for protection of components.
  • The triangle/arrow indicates forward direction of conventional current.
Teaching tips & guidance
  • Analogy: a one‑way turnstile — show with arrows on board which way charges can pass (conventional vs electron).
  • Stretch: link to non‑ohmic I–V graphs; threshold voltage concept.

Answer: Diode

Answer: direct current

Answer: cathode

Answer: non-linear

5) Series Circuits — Current

  • In a series circuit, components are in a single loop.
  • The current is the same at every point in a series circuit.
  • If you increase the total resistance (more components), current I decreases for a given V; if voltage increases, current increases.
Teaching tips & guidance
  • Demo: put two identical lamps in series; ask which is brighter vs a single lamp — then explain current limit by total R.
  • Assessment: sketch current values around the loop; all must match.

Answer: A

Answer: more resistance

6) Parallel Circuits — Current & Junctions

  • In a parallel circuit, components are on separate branches.
  • At a junction: total current in = total current out (current splits and recombines).
  • In identical branches, the current splits equally.
Teaching tips & guidance
  • Use water analogy: two parallel pipes offer more routes → greater total flow (lower equivalent resistance).
  • Checkpoint: add two ammeters on each branch and one at the supply to verify conservation of current.

Answer: charge

Answer: sum

Answer: decreases
Two identical lamps in parallel are ____ compared to one lamp alone.
Answer: brighter individually

Answer: stay on

7) Placing Ammeters

  • Place ammeters in series with the part of circuit whose current I (in A) you want to measure.
  • Series ammeters read the same current in a given branch. Use multiple ammeters to compare branch currents.
Teaching tips & guidance
  • Troubleshoot: if the meter reads 0, check it isn’t across the battery and that range/lead sockets are set to A.
  • Exam tip: at a junction, label currents with arrows before calculating.

8) Electromotive Force (e.m.f.)

  • The e.m.f. is the total energy per unit charge supplied by a source, measured in V.
  • Cells in series add: total E = E₁ + E₂ + ….
  • In a series circuit, components share the supply’s e.m.f. so that V_total = V₁ + V₂ + ….
Teaching tips & guidance
  • Whiteboard: draw a bar model showing how the battery’s energy per coulomb is distributed across components.
  • Misconception: students often think voltage ‘gets used up’. Emphasise energy transfer, not charge loss.

Mini-quiz (answers visible in teacher copy)

Answer: V

Answer: Yes

Answer: 7 V

Answer: charge

Answer: 6 V
In series, if one component has zero drop, others take…
Answer: more of the e.m.f.
What symbol often denotes e.m.f. in diagrams?
Answer: E

9) Potential Difference in Parallel

  • In parallel, the potential difference is the same across each branch.
  • So if the supply is 12 V, each branch also has 12 V.
Teaching tips & guidance
  • Practical: put a voltmeter across each branch in a parallel board — all read the same as the supply.

10) Equivalent Resistance in Parallel

  • For two resistors in parallel, the combined resistance R is found from 1/R = 1/R₁ + 1/R₂
  • For equal resistors R in parallel, the total is R/2 (two in parallel), R/3 (three in parallel), etc.
  • The equivalent resistance in parallel is always less than the smallest individual resistance. Units: Ω.
Teaching tips & guidance
  • Memory trick: ‘parallel paths’ → ‘more lanes’ → lower overall resistance.
  • Worked check: calculate current from I = V/R_total and compare to sum of branch currents.

11) Potential Divider (Two Resistors)

  • A potential divider splits the supply V_in across two series resistors R1 and R2.
  • The lower resistor’s output is V_out = (R2 / (R1 + R2)) · V_in.
  • Using sensors (e.g., LDR or thermistor) as R1 or R2 makes V_out change with light or temperature.
Teaching tips & guidance
  • Modelling: use two real resistors and a 10–12 V supply; measure Vout while swapping resistance values.
  • Exam cue: identify which resistor is across the output — that one goes in the numerator of the ratio.

Mini-quiz (answers visible in teacher copy)

In a divider, if R1 = R2, then Vout is…
Answer: ½ Vin
If R2 increases (R1 fixed), Vout…
Answer: increases
Divider formula is…
Answer: V_out = (R2/(R1+R2)) · V_in
Using an LDR as R2 makes Vout larger in…
Answer: bright light
Units of resistance used in figure are…
Answer: kΩ
If Vin = 12 V, R1 = 20 kΩ, R2 = 10 kΩ → Vout…
Answer: 8 V
A potential divider uses resistors in…
Answer: series
The meter used to measure Vout is a…
Answer: voltmeter
Replacing R2 with an NTC thermistor makes Vout…
Answer: rise when hot
Replacing R2 with an LDR makes Vout…
Answer: rise with light

12) Electrical Safety & Mains Wiring

  • Danger: excessive current can overheat cables and cause fire. Use appropriate fuses and do not overload extension leads.
  • Mains plugs and appliances use live, neutral and earth conductors; proper connections and cable grip are essential for safety.
  • Metal-cased appliances must be earthed; the fuse disconnects supply under fault by melting.
Teaching tips & guidance
  • Practical check: ask students to identify live/neutral/earth on a real plug and choose the correct fuse rating.
  • Discussion: why is the earth wire connected to the case and not the neutral? (Fault current path that trips protection)
